<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1560,2019]" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,318,1706,1730]" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species differs from most other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1878" box="[719,840,1707,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Teracotona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[719,840,1707,1730]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Teracotona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa by a having monochromatic scarlet hindwing with a black spot at the cell apex and without spots at the outer margin. It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[1025,1167,1742,1766]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Teracotona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submacula">
<emphasis box="[1025,1167,1742,1766]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">T. submacula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1182,1297,1742,1767]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[154,1426,605,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-260@2.[151,1436,596,1848]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Adult specimens, genitalia, and pupa of Teracotona spp. (A–B, E–G, J–L) T. rhodophaea from Zanzibar Island [coll. RMBH]: (A) male; (B) female; (E) male genitalia; (F) aedeagus; (G) female genitalia; and (J–L) pupa (ventral, dorsal, and lateral view, respectively). (C–D, H–I) T. submacula from South Africa [coll. RMBH]: (C–D) males from Kwazulu-Natal and Limpopo provinces, respectively; (H) male genitalia; and (I) aedeagus. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna and Vitaly M. Spitsyn)." pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Fig. 2C–D</figureCitation>
) by having a more elongated forewing apex, larger size, a specific valva shape (compare 
<figureCitation box="[972,1141,1778,1803]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[154,1426,605,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-260@2.[151,1436,596,1848]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Adult specimens, genitalia, and pupa of Teracotona spp. (A–B, E–G, J–L) T. rhodophaea from Zanzibar Island [coll. RMBH]: (A) male; (B) female; (E) male genitalia; (F) aedeagus; (G) female genitalia; and (J–L) pupa (ventral, dorsal, and lateral view, respectively). (C–D, H–I) T. submacula from South Africa [coll. RMBH]: (C–D) males from Kwazulu-Natal and Limpopo provinces, respectively; (H) male genitalia; and (I) aedeagus. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna and Vitaly M. Spitsyn)." pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Fig. 2E and 2H</figureCitation>
), and a shorter and broader uncus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1560,2019]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,572]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="99" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,666,1850,1875]" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
Morphology of preimaginal stages: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[602,666,1851,1874]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Eggs:</emphasis>
</emphasis>
spherical, crème-white, glossy (
<figureCitation box="[1011,1096,1850,1875]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Incubation time 4 and 10 days under an average air temperature of 30ºC and of 19–20ºC, respectively. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[924,962,1886,1910]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">L1:</emphasis>
The length 
<quantity box="[1092,1154,1887,1911]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
at hatching and 
<quantity box="[1333,1394,1887,1911]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
before the first molt; head capsule brown, eyes black; ground color brown; 6–10 small verrucae with tufts of long hairs on each abdominal segment dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[527,642,1958,1983]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Fig. 1B–E</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[663,701,1958,1982]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">L2:</emphasis>
The length after molting 
<quantity box="[981,1074,1959,1983]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="6.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="3.0">3–9 mm</quantity>
; head capsule brown; eyes black; ground color brown; coloration of 1–2 first anterior and 2–4 last posterior abdominal segments lighter than that of other segments; each segment at the middle section of the body bears 14 verrucae with long hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1258,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig. 1F–G</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1276,1315,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="99">L3:</emphasis>
The length up to 
<quantity box="[217,297,188,212]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
; similar to L2 but differs by larger verrucae with longer hairs; 8 to 12 verrucae per body segment (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig. 1H–K</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,279,223,247]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="99">L4:</emphasis>
The length after molting up to 
<quantity box="[625,705,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
; head capsule dark-brown; eyes black; ground color dark-brown or black; each body segment bears 8 to 12 large verrucae with dense tufts of long hairs; the hairs on posterior and anterior sections of the body are black; those in the middle of the body are yellow or reddish yellow (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1259,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig. 1L–O</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1278,1307,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="99">L5</emphasis>
: The length at molting up to 
<quantity box="[329,407,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="23.0">23 mm</quantity>
; similar to L4 but differs by having larger verrucae with longer hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1157,1272,331,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig 1 P–Q</figureCitation>
); each segment bears two white spots laterally (one from each side). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[715,754,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="99">L6:</emphasis>
The length at molting up to 
<quantity box="[1057,1135,367,391]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="45.0">45 mm</quantity>
; looks like L5 but differs by having larger verrucae with longer hairs (
<figureCitation box="[593,707,403,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-18@1.[196,1390,180,1897]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eggs and larvae of Teracotona rhodophaea. (A) Eggs. (B–E) First instar larvae. (F–G) Second instar larvae. (H–K) Third instar larvae. (L–O) Fourth instar larvae. (P–Q) Fifth instar larvae. (R–S) Sixth instar larvae. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig 1 R–S</figureCitation>
); each segment bears two white spots laterally (one from each side). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,218,440,463]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Pupa:</emphasis>
Total length 
<quantity box="[355,472,439,463]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="18.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="16.0">16–21 mm</quantity>
; motionless; maximum width 
<quantity box="[789,893,440,464]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="9.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.0">8–10 mm</quantity>
; almost entirely black or dark-brown, slightly shiny (
<figureCitation box="[159,276,475,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[154,1426,605,1836]" captionTargetId="figure-260@2.[151,1436,596,1848]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Adult specimens, genitalia, and pupa of Teracotona spp. (A–B, E–G, J–L) T. rhodophaea from Zanzibar Island [coll. RMBH]: (A) male; (B) female; (E) male genitalia; (F) aedeagus; (G) female genitalia; and (J–L) pupa (ventral, dorsal, and lateral view, respectively). (C–D, H–I) T. submacula from South Africa [coll. RMBH]: (C–D) males from Kwazulu-Natal and Limpopo provinces, respectively; (H) male genitalia; and (I) aedeagus. (Photos: Elizaveta A. Spitsyna and Vitaly M. Spitsyn)." pageId="2" pageNumber="99">Fig. 2A–C</figureCitation>
); antennae and legs weakly seen; abdominal spiracles narrow, slightly rising above the cuticular surface, with orange inner side; in a silken, loosely spun, brownish cocoon. The pupal development takes 36–76 days.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption pageId="1" pageNumber="98" startId="1.[151,250,1922,1946]" targetBox="[196,1390,180,1897]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1922,2018]" pageId="1" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,1922,1946]" pageId="1" pageNumber="98">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
Eggs and larvae of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1865" box="[497,743,1922,1946]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Teracotona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodophaea">
<emphasis box="[497,743,1922,1946]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="98">Teracotona rhodophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[759,795,1922,1946]" pageId="1" pageNumber="98">(A)</emphasis>
Eggs. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[871,934,1922,1946]" pageId="1" pageNumber="98">(B–E)</emphasis>
First instar larvae. 
